The LinearClassifier op is not enabled by default in the mobile package.
This file shows which ones are:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/4daa14bc74b5378d5fcb0d6de063a9fa8bd42eac/tools/ci_build/github/android/mobile_package.required_operators.config
You can do a custom build to get the ops you need.
https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/tutorials/mobile/custom-build.html
https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/build/reduced.html
Sorry, some of the pages at onnxruntime.ai/docs seem to have some broken links at the moment.

Need I rebuild and install onnxruntim package in python environment?
Thanks.

Hi @edgchen1 ï¼Œ
     ONNX Runtime Mobile Custom Build introduces how to create a custom 'minimal' build for Android.   It requires to add --include_ops_by_config to the build parameters, it will build a onnxruntim which only support my custom model.  If I have many models, how to do custom building? How to do full build for Android?
     Besides, does onnxruntime support sklearn-baggingClassifier ?
Thanks.

> Need I rebuild and install onnxruntim package in python environment?

Right. If you want to use the --use_nnapi conversion option, you can build onnxruntime with the NNAPI EP enabled (--use_nnapi build.py option). Use the build.py --build_wheel option to produce a Python wheel.

> If I have many models, how to do custom building?

The conversion script can actually support multiple models and generate the configuration including the ops needed by all of them. Just pass the directory that contains your models.

> How to do full build for Android?

If you do not want to have a reduced set of ops, just don't use the --include_ops_by_config build.py option and all of the ops will be included. If you want a build with full functionality (e.g. loading ONNX models) and the binary size that comes with it, don't use the --minimal_build build.py option.

> Besides, does onnxruntime support sklearn-baggingClassifier ?

Sorry, not familiar with that myself - you could try it in a full build and see.

For reference, NNAPI is for DNN only, which will not support traditional ML ops, if your models use a lot of traditional ML ops, the model conversion using official ONNX Runtime pypi package is sufficient (without using `--use_nnapi` option)

The compile failed when trying to build the protobuf compiler (protoc) for your host system (Windows), it cannot use the NDK C/C++ compiler since that's for cross-build Android binaries.
The simplest way to resolve this is to start the building process from a Visual Studio Developer Command Prompt, see https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/visualstudio/ide/reference/command-prompt-powershell?view=vs-2019
Or you can prebuild protoc.exe from `<onnxruntime root>cmake/external/protobuf` (you will need to sync the submodule first) and add `--path_to_protoc_exe=<path to your protoc.exe>` to the build command.
